Why the shift from to is AI-specific.
The increase in asset elasticity captures three mechanisms absent from standard Cobb-Douglas capital accumulation. First, data feedback loops: firms with larger customer bases generate more training data, improving AI performance and attracting more customers (Farboodi and Veldkamp, 2022)—a self-reinforcing cycle absent from physical capital. Second, compute scaling: AI model performance scales as a power law with compute investment (Kaplan et al., 2020), favoring firms that can amortize fixed compute costs across large user bases. Third, winner-take-most dynamics in AI markets: AI product quality has a discontinuous payoff structure where the best model captures disproportionate market share, unlike physical capital where quality differences translate linearly into market outcomes.
Distinguishing from standard capital deepening.
The concentrating channel differs from standard capital deepening in that AI simultaneously compresses skill-based variance and amplifies asset returns, the shift in effective occurs over years rather than decades, and the relevant capital is intangible with near-zero marginal replication cost, creating winner-take-most dynamics (Haskel and Westlake, 2018). This generates a testable prediction: the correlation between within-occupation wage compression and between-firm wage divergence should be positive in AI-exposed sectors.
